Title: MINT CONDITION
Credit: written by
Author: Joshua Brooks
Draft date: First Draft
Notes: Goofball cartoon comedy, Ace Ventura energy, played at full commitment. The Shine sequences are shot like a beautiful drug trip. The taper subplot runs underneath as texture -- true, mundane, never the whole joke.
Contact: --

/* TONE NOTE: Big. Physical. Cartoonish. The camera does whip-pans. The score does needle-scratches. And yet: every absurd person in this movie believes their life completely, and the two quietest scenes in it -- a pharmacist saying "Thursday" and a man saying "it was a fair trade" -- are played dead straight, which is what makes the rest allowed to be enormous. */

FADE IN:

EXT. BLISS MANOR -- MONTECITO, CALIFORNIA -- DAWN

A coastal estate so large it has weather. Fountains. Topiary shaped like famous economists. A driveway you could land a Cessna on, and, judging by the windsock, someone does.

TITLE: "MINT CONDITION"

INT. BLISS MANOR -- THE HALL OF THINGS -- DAWN

A gallery the length of a bowling alley. Lit like the Louvre. And in the cases:

-- The actual puck from the Miracle on Ice.
-- A Stradivarius. Next to it, a second Stradivarius, with a small card reading "BACKUP."
-- Napoleon's smaller, angrier hat.
-- An Action Comics #1, framed beside a handwritten note from the seller that just reads "please stop calling me."

At the end of the hall, in a bathrobe over silk pajamas, stands RANDOLPH "RANDY" BLISS, 52 -- silver-maned, boyish, a face built for delight and currently not using it. He holds a smoothie he will not drink.

He is staring at the room's only EMPTY CASE.

Museum-lit. Velvet plinth. A brass plaque, already engraved, reading: "SOON."

HIS BUTLER, OSWALDO, 60s, dignified beyond all surrounding evidence, approaches with a silver tray. On the tray: a single pill bottle and a glass of water.

OSWALDO
Your seven a.m., sir. Doctor Nam reminds you it is now the half dose. She asks me to say, quote, "the taper only works if it tapers."

RANDY
(taking the half pill; eyeing it like a demotion)
It's the size of a hyphen, Oswaldo.

OSWALDO
Progress, sir.

RANDY
(swallowing it; still staring at the empty case; the real subject arriving)
Any word from Geneva?

OSWALDO
The gentleman in Geneva was a hoax, sir. As was the gentleman in Osaka, the widow in Tampa, and the man who claimed his was buried with his father.

RANDY
And was it?

OSWALDO
You paid to exhume the father, sir. It was a Blastoise.

Randy closes his eyes. A man bearing up.

RANDY
A Blastoise.

OSWALDO
In fairness to the deceased, near mint.

INT. BLISS MANOR -- SCREENING ROOM -- CONTINUOUS

Randy at a touchscreen wall. Oswaldo at his shoulder. On screen: a corporate-espionage-grade dossier. Title slide:

INSERT -- SCREEN: "THE 1998 'CRYING CHARIZARD' PROMO. Printed: 8. Confirmed surviving: 7. Location status follows."

RANDY
(reciting it like scripture; he needs no slides; the slides are for us)
Eight cards, Oswaldo. Printed for the eight finalists of the '98 Osaka Invitational. The artist was going through a divorce -- it's the only card in history where Charizard is crying. One single tear. He's still breathing fire. But he's crying while he does it.
(beat; hand to chest)
It's the most emotionally complicated piece of cardboard ever made.

OSWALDO
So you have said at four weddings, sir.

The screen flips through THE LEDGER OF EIGHT -- each card copy, numbered, with a status:

-- No. 1: POKÉMON COMPANY ARCHIVE, TOKYO. "Unbuyable. I've tried. There were lawyers." 
-- No. 2: THE SMITHSONIAN. "Don't ask. There is a restraining order with my name spelled correctly."
-- No. 3: LOST AT SEA, 2003. Yacht "Papa's Bonus" went down off Catalina.
-- No. 4: SISTER BEATRICE, Carmelite convent, Fresno. Uses it -- unconfirmed -- as a BOOKMARK.
-- No. 5: UNKNOWN. Last seen changing hands in a Denny's parking lot, Reno, 2011.
-- No. 6: DESTROYED. A dog. There was a dog. We don't discuss the dog.
-- No. 7: "DUANE."

The screen just says DUANE, in red, with no other data, like a curse.

OSWALDO
And number eight, sir?

Randy doesn't answer. The question is a formality; Oswaldo asks it the way you check a wound.

MATCH DISSOLVE TO:

EXT. CUL-DE-SAC -- MODESTO -- 1985 -- DAY [FLASHBACK]

Sun-bleached, VHS-warm. YOUNG RANDY, 11, chubby, radiant, holds a CARD in a plastic sleeve -- and around it the light literally bends, holofoil rainbows crawling the frame. The Shine, before we know its name.

/* Note: yes, the card didn't exist in 1985. The film knows. The flashback is memory, not history -- it is sun-bleached AND wrong, like all origin stories. If anyone asks, Randy insists it was 1985, "the summer of the trade," and no fact-checker has survived contact with him. */

Across from him: YOUNG DUANE, 11, a small boy with the eyes of a regional bank manager. He holds, sweating in the Modesto heat: one (1) CAPRI SUN. Warm. Fruit Punch.

YOUNG DUANE
Straight trade.

YOUNG RANDY
(licking dry lips; a mouth like the Mojave; eleven years old and about to learn what he's made of)
It's... warm.

YOUNG DUANE
Trade's the trade.

HOLD on Young Randy's face. The thirst. The card. The thirst. The card.

His hand extends the card in terrible slow motion --

SMASH CUT TO:

INT. BLISS MANOR -- SCREENING ROOM -- PRESENT

RANDY
(quietly; to the screen; a man reciting his own autopsy)
I didn't even finish it. It got hot in the sun and I drank maybe a third.

OSWALDO
I know, sir.

RANDY
He kept the pouch, Oswaldo. He had it BRONZED. It's in his lobby.

OSWALDO
I know, sir.

RANDY
(turning from the screen; robe swirling like a cape; the quest declared for the four-hundredth time but today it has teeth)
Ledger says a copy surfaces at Collect-A-Con Anaheim this weekend. Number Five. The Denny's card. It's real this time -- The Laminator authenticated the scans.

OSWALDO
The Laminator once authenticated a Pikachu drawn in crayon, sir.

RANDY
He was younger then. We were all younger then.
(heading for the door; then stopping; the other errand; his voice dropping to something human)
And Oswaldo -- we have to swing by the MediSaver first. Refill day.

OSWALDO
(checking a small notebook; delicately)
Sir... refill day is Thursday. Today is Tuesday.

A silence. Randy's jaw sets like a man hearing distant artillery.

RANDY
Gloria.

INT. MEDISAVER PHARMACY -- VAN NUYS -- DAY

A strip-mall pharmacy. Fluorescent. A short line of ordinary citizens. And at the counter, in a lab coat, immovable as a continental shelf: GLORIA, 55, pharmacist. She has seen everything and dispensed exactly what was prescribed, when it was prescribed, since 1994.

Randy approaches the counter the way his security detail wishes he wouldn't: alone, smiling, leading with charisma.

RANDY
Gloria! You look radiant. New lanyard?

GLORIA
(not looking up)
It's Thursday, Mr. Bliss.

RANDY
See -- and this is fascinating -- it's actually Tuesday --

GLORIA
The refill is Thursday. Twenty-eight days. It was twenty-eight days last month and, in a twist, it is twenty-eight days this month.

RANDY
Gloria. G. I'm about to travel. Anaheim. High-stakes environment, lot of stimulation, lot of LED walls --

GLORIA
Thursday.

RANDY
(leaning in; lowering his voice; going to the move that has never once failed him in thirty years)
What if I told you... that there is a boat --

GLORIA
Mr. Bliss, if you offer me the boat again I am legally required to log it.

RANDY
It's a different boat.

GLORIA
(stamping something with terrible finality)
Thursday.

Randy stands there. A man worth $4.1 billion, at a linoleum counter, in front of the only human being on earth with an actual "no" in her.

Behind him in line, an OLD MAN with a cane:

OLD MAN
She's right, you know. Rules is rules.

RANDY
(wheeling on him; catching himself mid-wheel; smoothing his jacket; the mood spike arriving and being ridden like a mechanical bull)
That's -- you know what, that's a beautiful sentiment, sir, and I hope your hip gets better.

OLD MAN
It's a knee.

RANDY
(already leaving; through teeth; with feeling)
I picked the wrong day to quit smoking.

OSWALDO
(holding the door; quietly)
You've never smoked, sir.

RANDY
Then it was Xanax. One of those. It was somebody's wrong day, Oswaldo.

EXT. ANAHEIM CONVENTION CENTER -- SATURDAY -- DAY

An aircraft-carrier of a building wearing an inflatable Pikachu the size of a church. Banners: "COLLECT-A-CON -- WEST COAST'S BIGGEST TRADING CARD EXPO." A river of humanity: kids, dealers, a man dressed as a Squirtle arguing with security about his shell being a bag.

Randy's motorcade -- three black Escalades -- pulls up. Randy emerges in "civilian disguise": a bucket hat, sunglasses, and a T-shirt reading "JUST A NORMAL CARD GUY."

OSWALDO
(deadpan; assessing the disguise)
Impenetrable, sir.

INT. COLLECT-A-CON -- MAIN FLOOR -- CONTINUOUS

BEDLAM. A thousand vendor tables. Glass cases of holofoil under halogen. A DJ, inexplicably. An autograph line for a man billed as "THE VOICE OF SEVERAL POKÉMON, ALLEGEDLY."

And LED WALLS -- enormous, strobing, everywhere.

Randy flinches at the light like a man being interrogated by it. He puts a second pair of sunglasses on over the first pair. Presses two fingers to his temple where the taper headache lives now, a small tenant with a lease.

OSWALDO
Sir?

RANDY
I'm fine. It's the half dose. Doctor Nam says the headaches are, quote, "the sound of the brain remodeling."
(beat; squinting through two pairs of sunglasses)
My brain's doing an open-concept kitchen, Oswaldo.

They push through the crowd toward Booth 404 -- and the crowd parts, and there it is:

BOOTH 404. A folding table. A locked glass case. And inside the case, on black velvet, under a single halogen spot:

THE CARD.

Crying Charizard. One tear. Still breathing fire.

And here comes THE SHINE -- the film's first full pour:

/* THE SHINE, SEQUENCE ONE: The convention SOUND falls away like water going down a drain. The crowd smears into slow watercolor. Every light in the building bends toward the card and comes off it in long taffy ribbons of holofoil rainbow. Somewhere, a choir that is definitely just one guy humming. Randy walks through the blurred crowd untouched, parting cosplayers like reeds, his two pairs of sunglasses reflecting a single point of light. It is ridiculous. It is genuinely beautiful. Both at once. That's the assignment. */

Randy arrives at the case. Presses one hand to the glass, gently, like visiting a relative in the hospital.

The sound CRASHES back in --

DEALER (O.S.)
NO TOUCHING THE GLASS.

Behind the table: the DEALER, 45, ponytail, fingerless gloves, a T-shirt of a wolf howling at a slightly different wolf. This is KEITH.

KEITH
You want to see the card, there's a viewing protocol. Hands behind your back. Breathe away from it. No flash photography -- the flash "excites the foil."

RANDY
(hands behind back; breathing away from it; utterly compliant; a lamb)
It's Number Five. The Denny's card. Reno, 2011 --

KEITH
(narrowing his eyes)
Nobody knows about Reno.

RANDY
I know about Reno, Keith. I've been to the Denny's. I bought the Denny's.

KEITH
(recalculating this customer entirely)
...It's not for sale. It goes to auction tonight. Private room. Invitation only. The list is locked.

RANDY
(removing both pairs of sunglasses; then the bucket hat; the full reveal, like a knight lifting his visor)
Keith. Look at me. Do you know who I am?

KEITH
(squinting; a long beat; then, with total confidence)
...You're the backup-beep guy. The truck-beep billionaire.

RANDY
(a wound opening behind his eyes)
That is DUANE. Duane HICKLE is the beep. I am the DOOR WEDGE. I am the reason hotel doors close QUIETLY, Keith. I gave the hospitality industry its SILENCE.

KEITH
(beat)
...The list is still locked.

RANDY
(putting the bucket hat back on; to Oswaldo, marching off; with the gravity of Churchill)
Get me into that room.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. COLLECT-A-CON -- SERVICE CORRIDOR -- NIGHT

Randy and Oswaldo, flattened against a wall like a heist team, watching a door marked "PRIVATE AUCTION -- CREDENTIALED ONLY." A bouncer the size of a vending machine checks lanyards.

A small voice from behind a stack of chairs:

DESTINY (O.S.)
You're doing it wrong.

They turn. From the shadows steps DESTINY, 9, gum, side ponytail, a binder under one arm thick enough to stop small-arms fire. She looks Randy up and down like a loan application.

DESTINY
You're the door-wedge guy. You've been to every big card show in the western region for three years asking about the Crying 'Zard. Vendors call you "Deep Pockets Sad Eyes."

RANDY
They call me --

DESTINY
Deep Pockets Sad Eyes. Yeah.
(cracking gum)
I can get you in that room. I run errands for the auctioneer. Badge access.
(she holds out her hand, flat)
Fifty bucks and your Escalade guy drives me to my nana's after. She's in Buena Park, it's like ten minutes.

RANDY
(to Oswaldo)
Pay her.

DESTINY
(pocketing the fifty; already walking; over her shoulder, the film's scariest negotiator establishing terms)
That was a test. It should've been five hundred and you folded instantly. We'll work on you.

INT. COLLECT-A-CON -- PRIVATE AUCTION ROOM -- NIGHT

A curtained ballroom section. Folding chairs, a podium, the CARD on a easel-mounted case under a spotlight. Forty bidders: collectors, two guys on phones speaking rapid Japanese, a woman with a falcon (unexplained, never addressed).

The AUCTIONEER -- tuxedo T-shirt, gavel that is clearly a rock-hammer -- takes the podium. Randy, in a borrowed STAFF vest over his disguise (Destiny's work), sits in the back row, vibrating.

AUCTIONEER
Lot One. The Reno Denny's Crying Charizard. Authentication by The Laminator himself --
(a murmur; someone crosses themselves)
-- grade pending. Opening bid: fifty thousand.

Paddles rise. The number climbs fast -- 75, 90, 120 --

Randy's paddle comes up: 150.

A phone-guy: 175. Randy: 200. The falcon woman: 225 -- via the falcon lifting one wing, which the auctioneer accepts without comment.

RANDY
(standing; done with increments; the door-wedge fortune entering the room)
One million dollars.

Dead silence. The falcon looks at its owner. The owner shakes her head, out.

AUCTIONEER
One million from the... staff member. Going once --

And then, from the doorway, a VOICE. A voice like a truck backing up -- flat, penetrating, engineered to be impossible to ignore:

DUANE (O.S.)
Two million.

The room turns. In the doorway, flanked by two assistants dressed identically to him: DUANE HICKLE, 52. Small. Neat. The eyes of a regional bank manager, forty years matured into the eyes of a regional bank. He holds -- and sips from, slowly, maintaining eye contact with Randy across the entire room -- a CAPRI SUN.

RANDY
(the word escaping him like steam)
Duane.

DUANE
(sipping; the pouch crinkling in the silence)
Randolph.

AUCTIONEER
(sensing history; delighted)
Two million from Mr. Hickle! Do I hear --

RANDY
Three.

DUANE
Four.

RANDY
FIVE.

DUANE
(examining his nails)
Seven.

The room is a tennis crowd now. Destiny, by the curtain, watches with the face of a scout at a draft combine.

RANDY
(sweating; the taper headache spiking; the LED spotlight suddenly very loud, if a light can be loud, and tonight it can)
Eight... million dollars.

DUANE
(and here he does it: he finishes the Capri Sun -- the long, wretched, air-sucking SLURP of a straw finding the bottom of a pouch -- into a microphone-quiet room, staring at Randy the entire time)
Ten.

Randy opens his mouth. And his phone RINGS -- loud, unsilenced, the ringtone the Pokémon theme because of course it is. He fumbles it out: "DR. NAM."

RANDY
(hissing into phone)
Not NOW, Doctor --

DR. NAM (V.O.)
(warm; clinical; oblivious)
Randy, my system flagged that you attempted an early refill Tuesday. We talked about this. How's the headache, one to ten?

RANDY
(eyes on Duane; on the card; on his life)
TEN. Everything is ten!

DR. NAM (V.O.)
That's the remodeling. Breathe into your belly, not your chest --

AUCTIONEER
Ten million going once --

RANDY
(phone in one hand, paddle in the other, a man being torn in half by two service providers)
ELEVEN! -- not you, Doctor -- ELEVEN MILLION --

AUCTIONEER
Eleven from staff! Going once -- going twice --

Duane raises one finger. Everything stops.

DUANE
(quietly; to the room; a scalpel)
Point of order. Is the gentleman even credentialed? He appears to be wearing a staff vest over a shirt that says "Just a Normal Card Guy."

Every head turns. The bouncer starts moving. Destiny facepalms into her binder.

RANDY
(backing toward the fire exit; paddle still raised; dignity in full retreat)
I picked -- and I want everyone in this room to know it -- the WRONG DAY to quit Xanax!

OSWALDO
(appearing at his elbow, steering him out)
Smoking, sir. This morning it was smoking.

RANDY
It's a RANGE, Oswaldo!

SMASH CUT TO:

EXT. ANAHEIM CONVENTION CENTER -- LOADING DOCK -- NIGHT

Randy sits on a milk crate, decredentialed, bucket hat in his hands. Oswaldo stands beside him. Inside, muffled, a gavel bangs: sold. To Duane. Ten million.

Destiny walks up. Sits on the next crate. Cracks her gum.

DESTINY
You bid like a tourist. You never bid your feelings. Your feelings were showing from space.

RANDY
(staring at nothing)
He drank the Capri Sun at me.

DESTINY
Yeah. That was cold.
(beat; she opens her binder; flips professionally; taps a page)
Look. Number Five was always going to Hickle -- he had it bought before the room opened, the auction was theater. He does it to you every time. You know why he does it to you every time?

RANDY
Because he's a small beeping demon.

DESTINY
Because you CHASE. Chasers pay retail.
(she snaps the binder shut; stands; delivers the act-one thesis with a nine-year-old's total authority)
You want a Crying 'Zard, Deep Pockets? Stop chasing the ones everybody knows about.
(beat)
Number Three's been sitting at the bottom of the ocean for twenty years, and the ocean doesn't know who you are.

Off Randy's face -- the Shine flickering at the edges of the frame, faint, like weather approaching --

RANDY
(standing; hat on; reborn)
Oswaldo. Buy me a submarine.

OSWALDO
(already dialing)
The yellow one, sir, or the serious one?

RANDY
(walking toward the Escalades, backlit by loading-dock light, cinema's stupidest hero shot played completely straight)
Both.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

EXT. PACIFIC OCEAN -- OFF CATALINA ISLAND -- DAY

A research vessel. Cranes. Crew. And swinging from the davits: a deep-sea submersible, serious and gray -- with, lashed to the deck behind it, inexplicably, a second, smaller, YELLOW submarine. Nobody discusses it. It is simply there, like the falcon.

INT. SUBMERSIBLE -- DESCENDING -- DAY

Cramped. Portholes. Randy in a jumpsuit he has had TAILORED. Beside him, a marine salvage PILOT, 40s, and -- in a child-sized jumpsuit, having negotiated her way aboard through means the film declines to investigate -- DESTINY, with her binder.

PILOT
Wreck's at ninety meters. "Papa's Bonus," eighty-foot Ferretti, went down in the '03 swell. Owner got out. His card binder did not.

DESTINY
(reading from her own binder)
Number Three was in a fireproof, waterproof collector's safe. Bolted in the master stateroom.
(to Randy)
Waterproof for like thirty minutes, by the way. Twenty years ago. Manage your expectations.

RANDY
(face pressed to the porthole; the deep blue going deeper; whispering)
He's down there. Crying. In the dark. For twenty years.

PILOT
(to Destiny; quietly)
Is he talking about a card?

DESTINY
(flipping a page)
Don't make eye contact when he's like this.

EXT. THE WRECK OF "PAPA'S BONUS" -- SEAFLOOR -- CONTINUOUS

Floodlights find her: a yacht on its side, coral-crusted, fish schooling through the flybridge. The name still legible on the transom. PAPA'S BONUS. A grouper the size of a loveseat watches the submersible with municipal indifference.

INT./EXT. WRECK -- MASTER STATEROOM -- CONTINUOUS

The submersible's robotic arm peels back a corroded door. Inside, amid drifting silt and a school of garibaldi: THE SAFE. Bolted to the deck, exactly as promised.

And as the floodlight hits it --

/* THE SHINE, SEQUENCE TWO -- UNDERWATER: The sonar pings slow into whale song. The silt swirls into holofoil galaxies. The garibaldi orbit the safe in a perfect ring, bright orange, like the world's stupidest halo. Randy's face at the porthole, bathed in gold light rising from a steel box that cannot possibly be emitting light, and is. One tear rolls down Randy's cheek in zero-gravity slow motion. It is the most beautiful shot in the film. It is about a Pokémon card. */

RANDY
(whisper)
Open it. Open it down here. I want to be with him when he sees the light.

PILOT
Sir, protocol is we raise the safe --

RANDY
OPEN IT, GARY.

The robotic arm grinds the safe open in a bloom of silt --

-- and inside, in a rotted plastic sleeve, held gently up to the porthole by the arm:

A MAGIKARP.

Common. Not even holofoil. And -- visible even through twenty years of seawater -- LAMINATED. Home-laminated. Bubbles in the plastic.

Long silence. The whale song stops. A single sonar ping, like a sad bell.

DESTINY
(finally; scholarly)
Huh. So the Reno story was real. The guy DID swap it at the Denny's in 2011.
(flipping binder pages; connecting it)
Which means Number Three isn't down here. Number Three's been in circulation for fourteen years, mislabeled as Number Five --
(she stops; looks up; the math landing)
-- which means Hickle's ten-million-dollar card is the Denny's card, and the Denny's card was never -- 

RANDY
(staring at the Magikarp; the beautiful terrible dawn of hope)
-- was never Number Five.
(turning to her; gripping the porthole frame)
Then where's the REAL Number Five, Destiny?

Destiny licks a finger. Turns one page. Rotates the binder to face him.

INSERT -- BINDER PAGE: a grainy photo of a NUN, 70s, serene, in full habit, reading a Bible in a Fresno garden. Poking out of the Bible, unmistakable to the trained eye, one corner of orange holofoil, used as -- yes -- a BOOKMARK.

DESTINY
Fresno, Deep Pockets. It's been in Fresno the whole time.

RANDY
(to the pilot; eyes never leaving the photo; the Shine already gathering at the frame's edges like dawn)
Gary. Surface. And someone get Oswaldo on the radio --
(beat; with destiny, lowercase and uppercase, in his voice)
-- I need a reason to be in a convent.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

EXT. CARMELITE CONVENT OF PERPETUAL QUIET -- FRESNO -- DAY

Adobe walls. A garden. Bees. A hand-painted sign: "ANNUAL CHARITY SILENT AUCTION -- SATURDAY -- ALL PROCEEDS TO THE ROOF."

A second, smaller sign, in the same serene hand: "THE ROOF IS VERY BAD."

INT. CONVENT -- VISITING PARLOR -- DAY

Spare. A crucifix. Two wooden chairs. In one: SISTER BEATRICE, 78, serene as a lake at dawn. In the other: Randy, in what his stylist described as "humble tycoon" -- a $9,000 sweater the color of oatmeal.

On the table between them: her BIBLE. And peeking from Ezekiel, one corner of orange holofoil. Randy cannot stop looking at it. It's like a fishhook in his eye.

SISTER BEATRICE
You've come a long way, Mr. Bliss.

RANDY
(eyes on the bookmark; wrenching them up; sweating oatmeal)
I -- yes. I heard about the roof. I care very deeply about... roofs. Roofing. The concept of shelter, spiritually --

SISTER BEATRICE
(gently)
You've come about my bookmark.

Beat.

RANDY
(all pretense collapsing at once, like the roof)
It was my card, Sister. Not that one -- one like it -- I traded it when I was eleven for a warm Capri Sun and I have spent forty-one years and roughly two hundred million dollars trying to make one moment of thirst not have happened.

Silence. Bees. Somewhere, a bell.

SISTER BEATRICE
(considering him a long moment)
A novice gave it to me in 1999. Her nephew was one of the Osaka eight. She said the little dragon was crying, and I should keep him somewhere he could hear the Psalms.
(she touches the Bible, fondly)
He's been in Ezekiel a long time. Bit of a demotion for him, honestly, but the ribbon broke.

RANDY
Name a number, Sister. Any number. I'll fix the roof. I'll fix every roof. I will build you a cathedral with a retractable dome like the Cowboys have --

SISTER BEATRICE
(serene; immovable; Gloria in a habit)
It's not for sale, Mr. Bliss.
(beat; and then, with the faintest twinkle of a woman who has read the auction catalog)
It is, however, Lot Forty. Saturday. For the roof.
(leaning in, confiding)
Silent auction. Which will be difficult for you, I suspect. You seem loud.

INT. CONVENT -- CHAPEL HALL -- SATURDAY -- DAY

Folding tables around the chapel perimeter. Casseroles. A quilt. Lot 12: "MYSTERY JAR." And at the far end, Lot 40: the BIBLE, open to Ezekiel, the card's corner gleaming. A clipboard and a pen on a string beside it.

The rules, hand-lettered: "WRITE YOUR BID. HIGHEST AT 3 PM WINS. SILENCE, PLEASE. GOD IS LISTENING AND SO ARE THE SISTERS."

The hall is full: parishioners, locals -- and card people. Word got out. Keith is here. The falcon woman is here, the falcon wearing a tiny ribbon for the occasion. Two of Duane's identical assistants circulate like beige sharks.

Randy enters -- and stops dead.

Across the hall, by the casseroles, sipping from a Capri Sun in a chapel: DUANE.

They lock eyes across forty feet of consecrated silence. Neither may speak. It is the Western standoff of the film, conducted entirely in eyebrow.

MONTAGE -- THE SILENT WAR, IN SILENCE:

-- Randy writes a bid on the Lot 40 clipboard: $100,000. Underlines it. Walks away casually.

-- Duane glides in, reads, writes. Walks away. Randy returns: $250,000 -- and beneath it, Duane's entry: $250,001. Randy's nostrils flare. A NUN materializes at his elbow with a finger to her lips before he even inhales.

-- Randy writes $1,000,000. Stares at Duane across the hall. Duane, without breaking eye contact, finishes his Capri Sun -- the SLURP obscene in the sacred quiet. Three nuns turn. Duane points at Randy. Randy mouths a word we cannot print in a chapel.

-- The bidding sheet fills. A second sheet is stapled on. Sister Beatrice, presiding by the Bible, watches the numbers climb with the tranquility of a woman watching God re-roof her convent in real time.

-- 2:58 PM. Randy writes his final number, shielding it with his body like a test answer: $4,400,000. He caps the pen. Stands guard over the clipboard, arms crossed, a bouncer for a Bible.

-- Duane approaches for one last bid. Randy does not move. Duane reaches for the pen on its string. Randy steps on the string. The pen stops six inches from Duane's hand, taut. The two men look at each other. A nun's shadow falls over them both. Randy lifts his shoe, slowly, with enormous piety.

-- Duane picks up the pen. Reads Randy's number. Looks at Randy. And -- the film slows down here -- puts the pen back. Doesn't bid. Walks away with a small strange smile that Randy will replay for days and we, the audience, should file away too.

-- 3:00 PM. A handbell rings, once.

SISTER BEATRICE
(the only voice permitted; reading the sheet; serene)
Lot Forty. The little dragon goes to Mr. Bliss.
(beat)
The roof thanks you. The roof thanks you very much.

The hall applauds -- silently, hands fluttering in the air, nun-style. Randy stands there with jazz hands raining around him, receiving the Bible into his arms like a newborn, and the Shine floods the chapel -- stained-glass light bending toward Ezekiel, the one guy humming somewhere in the rafters --

RANDY
(whispering, to the card, finally, after forty-one years)
Let's go home.

EXT. CONVENT -- PARKING LOT -- MOMENTS LATER

Randy strides to the Escalades cradling the Bible. Destiny falls in beside him, Oswaldo behind, a papal procession with gum.

DESTINY
Congratulations. You paid four-point-four for a card in a Bible with zero paperwork.
(beat; the professional caveat)
It's raw, Deep Pockets. Unauthenticated, ungraded. Until GradeCorp seals it, it's a rumor with a tear on it. Hickle's people will say it's the fake and his is real.

RANDY
(supremely, dangerously serene)
Then we grade it. Monday. The clean room. The full ceremony.
(beat; to the sky; to the card; to Modesto, 1985)
Nothing on this earth can touch me now.

OSWALDO
(quietly; checking his notebook; the smallest cloud crossing the sun)
Sir -- gentle reminder -- Thursday came and went during the convent reconnaissance. You never picked up the refill. You are now... several days into zero.

A beat. Randy's left eye twitches, once, delicately, like a seismograph registering something far away and enormous.

RANDY
(still serene; mostly)
I feel fantastic, Oswaldo.

DESTINY
(to Oswaldo; low)
His eye's doing the thing.

OSWALDO
(low)
I know. I'll pack the electrolytes.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

EXT. INTERSTATE 5 -- GRAPEVINE -- MONDAY -- DAWN

The Escalade convoy southbound. Fog on the pass.

INT. LEAD ESCALADE -- CONTINUOUS

Randy in the back, the Bible in a custom foam-lined case on his lap, seatbelted into its own seat. He has not slept; the zero-Xanax days show in a fine full-body hum, like a tuning fork somebody struck last Tuesday.

The convoy pulls into a GAS STATION.

EXT. GAS STATION -- GORMAN -- CONTINUOUS

Randy paces the parking lot while the tanks fill. Fluorescent light through the fog. He squints at it -- the light sensitivity now a full-time roommate -- and drifts inside.

INT. GAS STATION -- CONTINUOUS

Randy at the hot case. Inside, under heat lamps possibly older than he is: taquitos, rotating with the slow menace of a planetarium exhibit. And a lone, sweating BREAKFAST BURRITO in shrink wrap, marked down twice.

DESTINY (O.S.)
Don't.

She's in the snack aisle with a Gatorade, watching him like a lifeguard.

RANDY
I haven't eaten since the chapel. My body is a temple and the temple is CLOSED for renovation, there's scaffolding everywhere, and the temple wants the burrito.

DESTINY
Your whole deal is chemistry right now. Doctor Nam said bland foods. Oswaldo has electrolytes and crackers in the car.

RANDY
(already at the register; the burrito warm in his hand like a decision being made by someone else)
Doctor Nam isn't the boss of the temple.

Destiny watches him eat it in four bites, standing up, by the windshield-wiper display. She takes out her binder and, on a fresh page, writes something down. We don't see what. We don't need to.

INT. GRADECORP HEADQUARTERS -- SANTA ANA -- LOBBY -- DAY

A cathedral of authentication. Marble. Behind glass: famous graded cards displayed like crown jewels. A motto etched in stone: "CONDITION IS TRUTH."

A RECEPTIONIST in a blazer. Security like an embassy. Randy, Oswaldo, and Destiny at the desk, the foam case handcuffed -- Randy insisted -- to Oswaldo's wrist.

RECEPTIONIST
Mr. Bliss. GradeCorp is honored. You've purchased our White Ceremony package --
(reading, with reverence)
-- witnessed authentication, live grading, immediate encapsulation. The card never leaves your sight.

RANDY
(hand on the glass; already misty)
The full ceremony. He deserves the full ceremony. He's been in Ezekiel.

RECEPTIONIST
Of course, sir.
(standing; grave)
You'll need to suit up. The Chamber is a Class 100 clean room. Positive-pressure garments, sealed at the wrists and ankles. Once the Ceremony begins, the Chamber is locked and the air is sacred.
(beat)
There is no re-entry, Mr. Bliss. And no early exit without triggering full contamination protocol.

A low, distant GURGLE. Everyone politely pretends it was the building.

DESTINY
(quietly; to Randy; the lifeguard again)
Bathroom's right there. Last chance. I'm serious.

RANDY
(striding toward the airlock, arms wide, destiny's idiot)
I've waited forty-one YEARS, Destiny. The temple can wait forty-one MINUTES.

INT. GRADECORP -- THE CHAMBER -- DAY

White. Silent. Beautiful. Air handlers whisper. In the center, under a surgical light: a single steel table. THE GRADER -- 60s, white bunny suit, magnifier loupe, the bearing of a man who has told popes their relics were reprints -- stands waiting.

Randy enters in his own bunny suit, sealed to the chin, hood up, only his face visible through the visor. Behind glass in an observation gallery: Oswaldo, Destiny, the receptionist -- and, arriving quietly at the back of the gallery with his two identical assistants, uninvited, entirely legal, holding a Capri Sun he cannot possibly have gotten through security: DUANE.

Randy sees him through the glass. Duane raises the pouch in a small toast.

GRADER
(sonorous; beginning the Ceremony)
We are gathered to witness the card.

The Grader unhouses the Bible with tongs. Opens it to Ezekiel. Lifts the card free -- and even the Grader, forty years in the business, pauses.

GRADER
...Oh, he IS crying.

/* THE SHINE, SEQUENCE THREE -- THE CHAMBER: the whitest room in California goes golden. The air handlers slow into breath. The surgical light bends around the card in ribbons; the Grader's loupe becomes a tiny sun. Through the visor, Randy's face: total peace. The one guy hums. For eleven perfect seconds, the movie is a religious painting. */

And then, very quietly, inside the sealed positive-pressure suit, the burrito announces itself.

A GURGLE -- but this time miked like a submarine hull under pressure. Randy's face, through the visor, does a thing no bunny suit can hide.

RANDY
(small; to no one; to God)
No.

GRADER
(oblivious; loupe down; beginning the examination)
Centering... fifty-five, forty-five. Strong. Surface... my word, the surface --

Randy begins to sweat. The suit -- sealed at wrists, ankles, neck -- is now a personal greenhouse for a developing weather system. He does the math on the airlock: LOCKED. The sign inside the door: "EARLY EXIT = FULL CONTAMINATION PROTOCOL. ALL MATERIALS IN CHAMBER WILL BE IMPOUNDED."

He looks at the card. At the door. At the card. It is the Capri Sun trade again -- the body versus the grail -- and his face knows it, and through the glass DESTINY knows it, standing now, palms on the window.

RANDY
(through teeth; clenched everything; a man negotiating with his own intestines like a hostage crisis)
Not now. Not HERE. We are in a CATHEDRAL --

GRADER
Corners... immaculate. Mr. Bliss, in thirty years I have never given the grade I am about to --

And the burrito, the taper, the fog, the four-point-four million, the forty-one years, all of it, arrives at once.

What follows, the film shoots like the tsunami it is: 

-- WIDE: Randy goes rigid, then briefly, horribly relaxed.

-- THE GALLERY: Oswaldo removes his glasses. Destiny turns around entirely and faces the back wall, hand raised, done.

-- THE SENSORS: a wall panel of air-quality readouts, all green, and then -- one by one, left to right, like a slot machine paying out in hell -- flipping to RED. A klaxon. A calm recorded voice:

CHAMBER VOICE (V.O.)
Particulate event detected. Particulate event detected. The Chamber is compromised.

-- THE GRADER: lowers his loupe. Looks at Randy. Says, with the same sonorous gravity as the opening rite:

GRADER
Sir. Condition is truth.

-- STROBES. Foam-nozzled response teams pouring through the airlock. The card -- THE CARD -- lifted from the table with tongs, slid into an orange bag stamped CONTAMINATED LOT, sealed, carried away from Randy's outstretched sealed-mittened hands as he is himself gently but firmly foamed.

RANDY
(on his knees in the foam; howling through the visor; the line arriving at its most inappropriate possible altitude, as designed)
I PICKED THE WRONG DAY TO QUIT SMOKING!

OSWALDO
(through the intercom; heartbroken; loyal to the end and to accuracy)
Xanax, sir. Today of all days, it was Xanax.

And through the gallery glass, in the strobing red light, Duane finishes his Capri Sun. SLURRRRP.

SMASH CUT TO:

INT. GRADECORP -- LEGAL CONFERENCE ROOM -- DAY

Randy, hair still foam-damp, in a GradeCorp-issue tracksuit, across a table from three LAWYERS and the receptionist, whose reverence has been replaced by paperwork.

LAWYER
Per the White Ceremony agreement -- section nine, "Contamination" -- all impounded materials are decontaminated and then liquidated at bonded auction to cover remediation costs. You may of course bid.
(beat)
The lot is scheduled for CardCon Las Vegas. Three weeks.

RANDY
It's MY card. I'll pay the remediation. I'll buy the chamber. I'll buy GradeCorp --

LAWYER
Mr. Hickle has already made a stalking-horse bid on the lot, sir. This morning.
(consulting a page; delicately)
He also purchased the naming rights to the incident. Legally, what happened in that room is now called "the Bliss Event."

Randy stares at the middle distance. Somewhere in the building, faintly, a floor buffer runs over the scene of his ruin.

INT. MEDISAVER PHARMACY -- VAN NUYS -- DAY

Rock bottom, fluorescent. Randy at Gloria's counter -- no charm, no boat, no disguise. Just a tired man in a GradeCorp tracksuit, several days past zero, holding his little paper script like a peace treaty.

GLORIA
(taking it; scanning; then, looking at him for the first time in the film like a person instead of a policy)
...You look terrible, Mr. Bliss.

RANDY
I lost him, Gloria.
(beat; the whole thing, simply)
I had him in my hands and my own body took him away from me.

Gloria regards him. Then turns, works, and sets an orange bottle on the counter. Slides it across.

GLORIA
Twenty-eight days.
(beat; and then, the only free thing she has ever given anyone)
Take it with food, Mr. Bliss. REAL food.
(beat)
And for what it's worth -- my grandson has that card in a magazine picture taped over his bed. Says the dragon's crying 'cause he's the strongest one and nobody asks if he's okay.

Randy looks up at her. Something lands.

GLORIA (CONT'D)
Thursday next month. Don't be early.

EXT. MEDISAVER -- PARKING LOT -- CONTINUOUS

Randy exits to find Destiny sitting on the hood of the Escalade -- a violation Oswaldo is visibly permitting -- with her binder open.

DESTINY
Hickle put out a press release.
(reading)
"Duane Hickle, inventor of the reverse-alert tone, will offer at CardCon Las Vegas, at public auction, TWO examples of the 1998 Crying Charizard promo: the recently remediated 'Bliss Event' card... and the Hickle Copy. Provenance: acquired 1985, Modesto. Consideration: one Capri Sun, fruit punch, warm."
(she looks up)
He's selling YOUR card, Deep Pockets. Both of them. In front of everybody. He doesn't even want the money.

RANDY
(quietly; understanding his enemy at last; the tuning-fork hum going still)
No. He wants me in that room, in a numbered seat, with a paddle. He wants to watch me chase.
(beat; he opens the pill bottle, shakes the day's half onto his palm, takes it with a swig of Destiny's Gatorade, hands it back; the smallest routine, finally done right)
Then let's give him something he's never seen me do.

DESTINY
Which is?

RANDY
(getting in the car; the hero shot again, but quieter now, and earned)
Read the trade.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

EXT. LAS VEGAS STRIP -- NIGHT

Neon. Fountains. A billboard the size of a hockey rink: "CARDCON LAS VEGAS -- THE AUCTION OF THE CENTURY -- 'THE TWO DRAGONS.'" Beneath it, in genuinely enormous letters: "FEATURING THE BLISS EVENT CARD."

RANDY (V.O.)
He named it after me. It's on a BILLBOARD, Oswaldo.

OSWALDO (V.O.)
Try to think of it as a wing of a hospital, sir.

INT. BLISS SUITE -- LAS VEGAS -- NIGHT -- [PREP MONTAGE]

The suite as war room. And the film's most responsible montage:

-- Destiny at a whiteboard: "RULE ONE: NEVER BID YOUR FEELINGS." Randy, in a chair, repeating it like a catechism.

-- Oswaldo laying out tomorrow's kit: suit, paddle, and -- in a labeled dopp kit -- the orange bottle, a sleeve of crackers, a banana. The film lingers one beat on the banana. Chekhov's bland food.

-- Randy on the phone with DR. NAM, actually listening, actually breathing into his belly. Through the window behind him, Vegas strobes; he has taped a hotel towel over the worst of the LED glare, a small dumb accommodation, the kind real people make.

-- Destiny slides a page across the table: the Capri Sun trade, diagrammed like a football play. An arrow from CARD to DUANE. An arrow from POUCH to RANDY. And circled, at the bottom, in a nine-year-old's handwriting, the question the whole film has been walking toward: "WHAT DID HE ACTUALLY WANT?"

-- Randy stares at it. Flashback-flicker: 1985, the trade -- but for the first time the memory plays past the handoff. Young Duane, card in hand, standing there afterward, waiting -- waiting for something Young Randy, already drinking, already leaving, never gave him. The memory can't say what. Randy falls asleep in the chair with the page on his chest.

INT. CARDCON -- GRAND AUCTION HALL -- DAY

A thousand seats. Press risers. The falcon, in a bow tie. Keith, weeping quietly in row thirty, moved just to be here. Onstage, twin easels under twin spotlights: TWO CARDS. Two crying Charizards, side by side, like the world's smallest, saddest twins.

At a podium: a real AUCTIONEER this time, tails and gavel. In the front row, at last, face to face with the room he built: DUANE, flanked by his identical assistants. A cooler of Capri Suns at his feet, iced, like champagne.

Randy enters -- suit, paddle number 007 (he paid for the number) -- flanked by Oswaldo and Destiny. He walks past Duane. Stops.

RANDY
(quietly; no audience for this but us)
Duane.

DUANE
(not looking up)
Randolph. Seat's marked. I bought you the good one. Sightlines to both.

RANDY
(studying him; the diagram in his breast pocket)
Why are you selling them?

DUANE
(now looking up; regional bank eyes; unreadable)
Everything's for sale, Randolph. You taught me that when we were eleven.

And there it is -- a hairline crack in the flat voice, forty years old, gone as fast as it came. Randy sees it. Files it. Takes his seat.

AUCTIONEER
Ladies and gentlemen -- Lot One. The remediated card. "The Bliss Event."
(a wave of laughter; Randy raises a hand and accepts it, graciously, like a man at his own roast)
Opening bid: one million dollars.

THE BIDDING WAR -- and the film gives it the full Vegas fight-scene treatment:

-- Paddles like gunfire. Two, four, six million. Phone bidders. The falcon bids twice, gets a look from its owner, stops.

-- Randy bids CALM. Flat increments. Never his feelings. Destiny beside him with the binder, calling numbers like a caddy reading greens: "He's stretching. Let the phone guy burn out. Now."

-- At eleven million it's Randy and one phone bidder. At twelve, the phone bidder folds. The gavel hovers --

-- and the taper headache arrives, one last time, a white spike behind the left eye, the spotlights suddenly knives. Randy grips the armrest. Doesn't reach for the dopp kit. Breathes into his belly. Peels the banana. EATS THE BANANA, in front of a thousand people, mid-auction, with total dignity. The headache crests. Passes.

AUCTIONEER
SOLD! The Bliss Event card -- to Mr. Bliss! Twelve million dollars!

The hall erupts. Randy sits perfectly still, one hand on his chest. He got one back. The room expects him to celebrate. He doesn't. Because --

AUCTIONEER (CONT'D)
And now. Lot Two. The Hickle Copy. Provenance: Modesto, 1985.
(beat; reading, as the hall goes quiet)
"Consideration: one Capri Sun. Fruit punch. Warm."

The card Randy held when he was eleven rises on its easel. And the Shine comes for him one final time --

/* THE SHINE, SEQUENCE FOUR -- FULL BLOOM: the auction hall pours away like paint in rain. Sound gone. A thousand people become wheat. The aisle to the stage becomes the cul-de-sac in Modesto, sun-bleached, VHS-warm, and the spotlight over the easel is the summer of 1985. Randy stands -- in reality, in the hall, a man standing silently at his seat while an auction rages unheard around him -- and in the Shine, an eleven-year-old walks toward his card down forty-one years of afternoon. */

DESTINY (O.S.)
(punching through the Shine, the only voice that can)
DEEP POCKETS. He's at THIRTY. Phone bidders are dead. It's you and him.

Sound crashes back. The hall. The board: $30,000,000. And the bidder -- paddle raised, bidding on HIS OWN CARD, driving it into the sun, eyes locked on Randy: DUANE.

RANDY
(standing in the aisle; understanding, finally, completely)
He's not selling it.
(to Destiny; to Oswaldo; to himself)
He was never selling it. It's a trap with a bow on it. He'll bid until I break, and if I win, he wins, because I'll have paid half my life for it, and he'll still have the pouch in his lobby.
(beat; the diagram; the crack in the flat voice; "he stood there waiting")
Because money was never what I paid him.

Randy hands his paddle to Destiny. Walks down the aisle. The hall murmurs. Security twitches; the Auctioneer freezes; Randy stops at the front row, in front of Duane, and reaches into his jacket --

-- and takes out a CAPRI SUN. Fruit punch. He's carried it since Van Nuys.

He holds it out. Warm. It's been in a jacket for three weeks. It is disgusting. It is perfect.

RANDY (CONT'D)
(quietly; a thousand people and no one but the two of them)
Straight trade.

DUANE
(staring at the pouch; the flat voice failing by degrees)
The card's at thirty million dollars, Randolph.

RANDY
I'm not bidding on the card, Duane. I'm re-running the trade.
(beat)
And this time I'm going to say the thing I didn't say when we were eleven. The thing you stood there waiting for while I walked away drinking.

The whole hall leans in. Duane's assistants lean in. The falcon leans in.

RANDY (CONT'D)
(and he means it; forty-one years of appraisal, revised)
It was a fair trade. You didn't cheat me. I was thirsty, and you had the only drink on the street, and you read the market and I signed. You won fair, Duane.
(beat; holding out the pouch)
I've just never been man enough to hear the beep. 

A silence like the chapel. Duane looks at the pouch. At Randy. Forty years of press releases and bronzed trophies and naming rights, all of it built to force this exact sentence out of this exact man, and now it's here and it's free.

DUANE
(finally; barely)
...It's warm.

RANDY
Trade's the trade.

Duane stands. Takes the pouch. And -- in front of a thousand people, God, and the falcon -- lifts the card off the easel himself and puts it in Randy's hands.

The hall detonates. The Auctioneer, ruined, gavels nothing, repeatedly. Keith faints into the arms of the Squirtle guy. Destiny, on her chair, arms up, screaming like it's a title fight. Oswaldo removes his glasses for the second time in the film, for a different reason.

And Randy holds the card. HIS card. The Shine rises --

-- and settles. Gentle. No taffy ribbons. No choir guy. Just a man, in ordinary light, holding a piece of cardboard with a crying dragon on it.

Because that's the joke, and the not-joke: it was never the card that glowed.

DUANE
(sipping the warm pouch; grimacing; delighted; the first honest face he's made in forty years)
This is revolting.

RANDY
I know. You get used to it around the third sip. 

INT. BLISS MANOR -- THE HALL OF THINGS -- DAY [ONE MONTH LATER]

The empty case. The brass plaque that read "SOON" -- being unscrewed by Oswaldo and replaced with a new one: "1985 -- 2026."

Inside the case, on the velvet plinth: the CARD, encapsulated at last, graded -- we push in -- GEM MINT 10. And propped beside it, in its own tiny frame, with its own tiny plaque: a bronzed CAPRI SUN pouch. Plaque: "CONSIDERATION."

/* Duane sent it. No note. There didn't need to be one. */

WIDER: the hall is not quiet. On the floor, cross-legged on a rug worth more than a house: RANDY and DESTINY, playing the actual card game with ordinary cards, arguing about a rule. Gloria's grandson is there too -- Randy flew him in; the kid is destroying them both. Somewhere a Capri Sun cooler sits open, iced.

Randy's phone buzzes. He checks it: "MediSaver -- Rx ready for pickup." He looks at the date. Thursday. Day 28, on the nose. He smiles, puts the phone away, and picks up his hand of cards.

DESTINY
Your turn, Deep Pockets. And don't bid your feelings.

RANDY
(laying down a card; utterly content; the last line of the film)
Kid -- feelings are all I've got left. Everything else, I traded fair.

He plays his card. The kids groan. Off the case -- the dragon, still crying, still breathing fire, home -- the light bends, just barely, one last time.

FADE OUT.

THE END